# SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Obtaining User Input with Prompt Dialogs

JavaScript provides three browser **dialog boxes**:

1. `alert(message)` ‚Üí displays info, OK button only.
2. `confirm(message)` ‚Üí returns `true` or `false`.
3. `prompt(message, default)` ‚Üí returns user input as a **string** (or `null` if cancelled).

```javascript
let name = prompt("Enter your name:", "Guest");
alert("Hello, " + name + "!");
let isAdult = confirm("Are you 18+?");   // boolean
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> `prompt()` **always returns a string**. You must convert to a number using `Number()`, `parseInt()`, or `parseFloat()` before performing arithmetic ‚Äî this is a classic KTU exam pitfall.

```javascript
let a = prompt("Enter first number");      // returns "5" (string)
let b = prompt("Enter second number");     // returns "3" (string)
let sum = a + b;                          // "53" (string concatenation!)
let correctSum = Number(a) + Number(b);   // 8 (numeric addition)
```

## 2.2 Arithmetic & Operators

### 2.2.1 KTU Formula Sheet ‚Äî Operator Precedence Cheat Table

> **Note:** Vertical bar in formula rows is escaped as `\mid` / `\vert` to preserve Markdown table integrity.

| Precedence | Category | Operators | Associativity | Example |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Grouping | `( )` | n/a | `(a + b) * c` |
| 2 | Member access / Call | `.`, `()`, `[]` | left-to-right | `obj.fn()` |
| 3 | Unary | `++`, `--`, `!`, `typeof`, `-x` | right-to-left | `!flag` |
| 4 | Multiplicative | `*`, `/`, `%` | left-to-right | `10 % 3` |
| 5 | Additive | `+`, `-` | left-to-right | `a + b` |
| 6 | Relational | `<`, `<=`, `>`, `>=` | left-to-right | `a < b` |
| 7 | Equality | `==`, `!=`, `===`, `!==` | left-to-right | `a === b` |
| 8 | Logical AND | `&&` | left-to-right | `a && b` |
| 9 | Logical OR | `\vert\vert` | left-to-right | `a \vert\vert b` |
| 10 | Assignment | `=`, `+=`, `-=`, `*=` | right-to-left | `x += 5` |
| 11 | Comma | `,` | left-to-right | `a, b, c` |

### 2.2.2 Special Arithmetic Operators

- `**` ‚Üí Exponentiation (ES2016): `2 ** 3 === 8`
- `++` (pre/post increment), `--` (pre/post decrement)
- `+x` ‚Üí unary plus, attempts numeric conversion
- `%` ‚Üí modulo (works with floats in JS): `5.5 % 2 === 1.5`

> [!NOTE]
> **Conceptual Analogy:** Precedence is like the **BODMAS rule** in mathematics ‚Äî higher precedence operations bind tighter. The order is *unary > multiplicative > additive > relational > equality > logical > assignment*.

### 2.2.3 Equality: `==` vs `===`

| Expression | `==` Result | `===` Result | Reason |
|---|---|---|---|
| `"5" == 5` | `true` | `false` | `==` coerces type |
| `null == undefined` | `true` | `false` | Special rule |
| `"0" == false` | `true` | `false` | Both coerce to `0` |
| `0 === -0` | `true` | `true` | `===` doesn't distinguish `+0`/`-0` |

> [!TIP]
> **KTU best practice (and exam answer):** Always use `===` (strict equality) to avoid **type-coercion bugs**.

## 2.3 Decision Making

JavaScript supports the classic `if / else if / else` ladder and the `switch` statement.

### 2.3.1 if / else Ladder

```javascript
let marks = 78;
if (marks >= 90) {
    grade = "A+";
} else if (marks >= 80) {
    grade = "A";
} else if (marks >= 70) {
    grade = "B";
} else if (marks >= 60) {
    grade = "C";
} else {
    grade = "F";
}
```

### 2.3.2 Ternary Operator

```javascript
let result = (marks >= 50) ? "Pass" : "Fail";
```

### 2.3.3 switch Statement

```javascript
let day = 3;
switch (day) {
    case 1: console.log("Monday");  break;
    case 2: console.log("Tuesday"); break;
    case 3: console.log("Wednesday");break;
    default:console.log("Other day");
}
```

> [!WARNING]
> Forgetting `break` causes **fall-through**, executing every case below. The `default` case is optional but strongly recommended.

## 2.4 Control Statements (Loops)

| Loop Type | When to Use | Min Executions |
|---|---|---|
| `while` | Unknown iterations, pre-test | 0 |
| `do‚Ä¶while` | At least one run required | 1 |
| `for` | Known count | 0 |
| `for‚Ä¶of` | Iterate iterables (arrays, strings) | 0 |
| `for‚Ä¶in` | Iterate object keys | 0 |

```javascript
// while loop
let i = 0;
while (i < 5) {
    console.log(i);
    i++;
}

// for loop
for (let j = 0; j < 5; j++) {
    console.log(j);
}

// do-while
let k = 0;
do {
    console.log(k);
    k++;
} while (k < 3);

// for...of (ES6)
let fruits = ["apple", "banana", "mango"];
for (const fruit of fruits) {
    console.log(fruit);
}

// for...in (over object keys)
let student = { name: "Anu", age: 20 };
for (const key in student) {
    console.log(key, student[key]);
}
```

### 2.4.1 Loop Control Statements

- `break` ‚Üí exits the loop entirely
- `continue` ‚Üí skips the current iteration

## 2.5 Functions

A **function** is a reusable block of code that performs a specific task.

### 2.5.1 Function Declaration (Hoisted)

```javascript
function add(a, b) {
    return a + b;
}
let sum = add(3, 5);   // 8
```

### 2.5.2 Function Expression

```javascript
const add = function (a, b) {
    return a + b;
};
```

### 2.5.3 Arrow Function (ES6)

```javascript
const add = (a, b) => a + b;
const square = x => x * x;        // single param, no parens
const greet = () => "Hello!";     // no params
```

### 2.5.4 Default Parameters

```javascript
function greet(name = "Guest") {
    return "Hello, " + name;
}
```

### 2.5.5 Rest Parameters & Spread

```javascript
function sum(...nums) {       // rest - collects args into array
    return nums.reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0);
}
let arr = [1, 2, 3];
console.log(sum(...arr));     // spread - expands array
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Conceptual Analogy:** A function is like a *vending machine*. You put inputs (coins, selection) and get back an output (snack). The internal mechanism is hidden ‚Äî this is **encapsulation**, a pillar of clean code.

## 2.6 Arrays

An **array** is an ordered, indexed (zero-based), heterogeneous collection. Arrays are **objects** under the hood in JavaScript (`typeof [] === "object"`).

### 2.6.1 Creation

```javascript
let arr1 = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
let arr2 = new Array(5);           // creates sparse array of length 5
let arr3 = Array.from("hello");    // ['h','e','l','l','o']
let arr4 = [10, "Kerala", true];   // heterogeneous allowed
```

### 2.6.2 Key Array Methods (KTU High-Yield)

| Method | Purpose | Returns | Mutates? |
|---|---|---|---|
| `push(x)` | add to end | new length | yes |
| `pop()` | remove from end | removed item | yes |
| `unshift(x)` | add to start | new length | yes |
| `shift()` | remove from start | removed item | yes |
| `splice(i, n, ...items)` | remove/insert | removed items | yes |
| `slice(start, end)` | copy portion | new array | no |
| `concat(arr)` | merge | new array | no |
| `indexOf(x)` | find index | number or -1 | no |
| `includes(x)` | check existence | boolean | no |
| `map(fn)` | transform | new array | no |
| `filter(fn)` | keep passing | new array | no |
| `reduce(fn, init)` | accumulate | single value | no |
| `forEach(fn)` | iterate | undefined | no |
| `find(fn)` | first match | element or undefined | no |
| `sort(fn)` | in-place sort | same array | yes |
| `reverse()` | reverse | same array | yes |

```javascript
let nums = [4, 2, 9, 1];
let squared = nums.map(n => n * n);            // [16, 4, 81, 1]
let evens   = nums.filter(n => n % 2 === 0);   // [4, 2]
let total   = nums.reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0); // 16
let sorted  = [...nums].sort((a, b) => a - b); // [1,2,4,9]
```

### 2.6.3 Spread & Destructuring

```javascript
let a = [1, 2], b = [3, 4];
let merged = [...a, ...b];          // [1,2,3,4]
let [first, second, ...rest] = [10, 20, 30, 40];
// first=10, second=20, rest=[30,40]
```

## 2.7 Classes (ES6)

JavaScript **classes** are *syntactic sugar* over **prototype-based inheritance**. They provide a cleaner, classical-OOP syntax for creating constructor functions.

### 2.7.1 Class Declaration

```javascript
class Student {
    // Constructor
    constructor(name, rollNo) {
        this.name   = name;
        this.rollNo = rollNo;
    }

    // Instance method
    introduce() {
        return `Hi, I'm ${this.name} (Roll ${this.rollNo})`;
    }

    // Static method (called on class, not instance)
    static school() {
        return "KTU Model School";
    }
}

let s1 = new Student("Anu", 21);
console.log(s1.introduce());         // Hi, I'm Anu (Roll 21)
console.log(Student.school());       // KTU Model School
```

### 2.7.2 Inheritance with `extends` and `super`

```javascript
class Graduate extends Student {
    constructor(name, rollNo, degree) {
        super(name, rollNo);          // calls parent constructor
        this.degree = degree;
    }
    introduce() {                     // method overriding
        return super.introduce() + `, ${this.degree}`;
    }
}
let g1 = new Graduate("Ravi", 7, "B.Tech CSE");
console.log(g1.introduce());         // Hi, I'm Ravi (Roll 7), B.Tech CSE
```

### 2.7.3 Getters & Setters

```javascript
class Circle {
    constructor(r) { this._r = r; }
    get area() { return Math.PI * this._r ** 2; }
    set radius(r) { this._r = r; }
}
let c = new Circle(5);
console.log(c.area);   // accessed as property
c.radius = 10;
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Conceptual Analogy:** A class is a *blueprint* (architect's plan), an object is the *house* built from it. The constructor is the *construction crew* that initializes the house.

## 2.8 Real-World Engineering Utility

JavaScript's fundamentals power:
- **Form validation** on registration/login pages
- **Dynamic UI updates** (Gmail, Facebook live feeds)
- **Single Page Applications** (React, Angular, Vue)
- **REST API calls** via `fetch` / `axios`
- **Server-side apps** via **Node.js** (Netflix, LinkedIn)
- **IoT & robotics** via Johnny-Five
- **Mobile apps** via React Native
- **Machine learning** via TensorFlow.js

<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

