# SECTION 3: Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Analytical Matrix ‚Äî Program Trace Table

This section presents an exhaustive **dry run** of representative KTU-typical programs, with step-by-step state transitions.

### 3.1.1 Trace 1 ‚Äî `prompt()` + Arithmetic + Decision

**Code:**

```javascript
let ageStr = prompt("Enter your age:");
let age    = Number(ageStr);
let category;

if (age >= 18 && age < 60) {
    category = "Adult";
} else if (age >= 60) {
    category = "Senior Citizen";
} else if (age > 0) {
    category = "Minor";
} else {
    category = "Invalid";
}

alert("Category: " + category);
```

**Dry Run (Assume user enters `"25"`):**

| Step | Statement | Variable State | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | `prompt("Enter your age:")` | `ageStr = "25"` | returns string |
| 2 | `Number(ageStr)` | `age = 25` | numeric conversion |
| 3 | `if (25 >= 18 && 25 < 60)` | condition ‚Üí `true && true ‚Üí true` | branch taken |
| 4 | `category = "Adult"` | `category = "Adult"` | assigned |
| 5 | `alert(...)` | displays `Category: Adult` | output |

**Edge case (user enters `"abc"`):**

| Step | Statement | Variable State | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | `prompt` | `ageStr = "abc"` | string |
| 2 | `Number("abc")` | `age = NaN` | Not a Number |
| 3 | `NaN >= 18` | `false` | NaN comparisons always false |
| 4 | `NaN >= 60` | `false` | skip |
| 5 | `NaN > 0` | `false` | skip |
| 6 | `else` | `category = "Invalid"` | output |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> `NaN` is **not equal to itself**: `NaN === NaN` is `false`. Use `Number.isNaN(x)` to test.

### 3.1.2 Trace 2 ‚Äî Control Statement (For Loop + Accumulator)

**Code:**

```javascript
let sum = 0;
let product = 1;
for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
    sum     += i;
    product *= i;
}
console.log("Sum =", sum, "Product =", product);
```

**Trace Table:**

| Iteration | `i` (pre-test) | `sum` after `+=i` | `product` after `*=`i | Exit? |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | 1 | 1 | 1 | no |
| 2 | 2 | 3 | 2 | no |
| 3 | 3 | 6 | 6 | no |
| 4 | 4 | 10 | 24 | no |
| 5 | 5 | 15 | 120 | no |
| ‚Äî | 6 | (loop not entered) | (unchanged) | yes (6>5) |

**Final Output:** `Sum = 15  Product = 120`

### 3.1.3 Trace 3 ‚Äî Function Call Stack

**Code:**

```javascript
function factorial(n) {
    if (n <= 1) return 1;
    return n * factorial(n - 1);
}
let result = factorial(4);
```

**Call Stack Unwinding:**

$$
\text{factorial}(4) = 4 \times \text{factorial}(3)
$$

$$
= 4 \times 3 \times \text{factorial}(2)
$$

$$
= 4 \times 3 \times 2 \times \text{factorial}(1)
$$

$$
= 4 \times 3 \times 2 \times 1
$$

$$
= 24
$$

**Stack trace in detail:**

| Call | Argument `n` | Base case? | Returns |
|---|---|---|---|
| factorial(4) | 4 | no | 4 √ó factorial(3) |
| factorial(3) | 3 | no | 3 √ó factorial(2) |
| factorial(2) | 2 | no | 2 √ó factorial(1) |
| factorial(1) | 1 | yes | 1 |
| factorial(2) | ‚Äî | ‚Äî | 2 |
| factorial(3) | ‚Äî | ‚Äî | 6 |
| factorial(4) | ‚Äî | ‚Äî | 24 |

### 3.1.4 Trace 4 ‚Äî Array Map / Filter / Reduce Pipeline

**Code:**

```javascript
let nums   = [10, 15, 20, 25, 30];
let result = nums
    .filter(n => n % 2 === 0)   // keep evens
    .map(n => n / 2)             // halve them
    .reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0); // sum
```

**Pipeline trace:**

| Stage | Input Array | Operation | Output |
|---|---|---|---|
| Initial | `[10,15,20,25,30]` | ‚Äî | ‚Äî |
| After `filter` | `[10,15,20,25,30]` | keep `n % 2 === 0` | `[10,20,30]` |
| After `map` | `[10,20,30]` | divide by 2 | `[5,10,15]` |
| After `reduce` | `[5,10,15]` | sum from 0 | `30` |

**Final:** `result = 30`

### 3.1.5 Trace 5 ‚Äî Class Instantiation & Inheritance

**Code:**

```javascript
class Animal {
    constructor(name) { this.name = name; }
    speak() { return `${this.name} makes a sound`; }
}
class Dog extends Animal {
    speak() { return `${this.name} barks`; }
}
let d = new Dog("Bruno");
console.log(d.speak());
```

**Trace:**

| Step | What happens | `d.name` | Method resolution |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | `new Dog("Bruno")` allocated in heap | uninitialized | constructor of `Dog` called |
| 2 | `super("Bruno")` ‚Üí Animal constructor | `"Bruno"` | parent constructor sets `name` |
| 3 | `d.speak()` invoked | `"Bruno"` | overridden `Dog.speak()` found first |
| 4 | returns `"Bruno barks"` | ‚Äî | output: `Bruno barks` |

> [!NOTE]
> JavaScript resolves methods using the **prototype chain** (`__proto__`). When `Dog` doesn't define a property, the lookup climbs to `Animal.prototype` and then `Object.prototype`.

## 3.2 Algorithm Analysis ‚Äî Big-O for Core Operations

| Operation | Time Complexity | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| Array `push/pop` | $O(1)$ | Amortized constant at tail |
| Array `shift/unshift` | $O(n)$ | All elements re-indexed |
| Array `splice` (middle) | $O(n)$ | Shifts tail elements |
| Array `indexOf/includes` | $O(n)$ | Linear scan |
| Array `map/filter/forEach` | $O(n)$ | Visits each element |
| Object property access | $O(1)$ avg | Hash-table lookup |
| String concatenation `+` | $O(n)$ | Creates new string |

## 3.3 Worked Derivation ‚Äî String Concatenation vs Arithmetic

**Problem:** Explain why `"5" + 3` yields `"53"` but `"5" - 3` yields `2`.

**Derivation:**

The `+` operator in JavaScript is **overloaded**:

1. If **both operands** are numbers (or coerce-able to numbers via `Number()`), perform **numeric addition**.
2. If **either operand** is a string, perform **string concatenation** (the non-string operand is converted via `toString()`).

For `+`:
- `"5" + 3` ‚Üí string `"5"` is encountered ‚Üí switch to concat mode ‚Üí `3.toString() = "3"` ‚Üí result is `"5" + "3" = "53"`.

For `-` (and other arithmetic operators):
- The `-` operator has **no string overload**. Both operands are coerced to numbers:
- `Number("5") - Number(3) = 5 - 3 = 2`.

$$
\text{Result of }+ = \begin{cases} \text{sum} & \text{if both operands are numeric} \\ \text{concatenation} & \text{if either is a string} \end{cases}
$$

$$
\text{Result of }-,\ *,\ /\ = \text{both operands coerced to } \text{Number},\ \text{then arithmetic applied}
$$

> [!IMPORTANT]
> This dual-nature of `+` is a **favourite KTU question**. Always use `Number()` or template literals `` ` ${x} ` `` to be safe.

