#### (b) Explain JavaScript classes with constructors, methods, inheritance, and the `super` keyword. Provide a working example. (7 Marks)

**Model Solution:**

**Theory (3 marks):**
- ES6 `class` is a **syntactic sugar** over prototype-based inheritance.
- `constructor()` initializes instance properties.
- Methods defined inside the class are added to the prototype.
- `static` methods belong to the class itself, not instances.
- `extends` enables inheritance; `super()` calls parent constructor.
- `super.method()` calls parent method (for overriding).

**Program (4 marks):**

```javascript
// Base class
class Vehicle {
    constructor(brand, speed) {
        this.brand = brand;
        this.speed = speed;
    }
    describe() {
        return `${this.brand} runs at ${this.speed} km/h`;
    }
}

// Derived class
class Car extends Vehicle {
    constructor(brand, speed, fuel) {
        super(brand, speed);     // call parent constructor
        this.fuel = fuel;
    }
    describe() {                  // method overriding
        return super.describe() + ` using ${this.fuel}`;
    }
    static type() {               // static method
        return "Four-wheeler";
    }
}

let myCar = new Car("Tesla", 200, "electric");
console.log(myCar.describe());     // Tesla runs at 200 km/h using electric
console.log(Car.type());           // Four-wheeler
```

**Explanation (4 marks):**
- Class declaration with `constructor` and instance method (1 mark).
- Inheritance via `extends` and parent invocation with `super()` (1 mark).
- Method overriding with `super.describe()` (1 mark).
- `static` method usage (1 mark).

